# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

llama.cpp's `common/chat.cpp` contains a dispatch function,
`common_chat_try_specialized_template()`, that matches a Jinja template's source text
against a set of marker strings and routes matching templates to dedicated
`common_chat_params_init_*` handler functions.  Those handlers build a PEG parser that
controls how the model's raw output is split into content, reasoning, and tool-call
fields.

The Mistral Instruct **v0.3** family (e.g. `mistralai/Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407`) uses
a distinctive format:
- User turns wrapped in `[INST]…[/INST]`
- System message prepended inline to the **first** user turn (no dedicated
  `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` wrapper)
- Assistant turns ended with `</s>` (the EOS token)
- Tool calls emitted as `[TOOL_CALLS][{"name":…,"arguments":{…},"id":"…"}…]</s>`

No existing handler covers this combination.  The closest is the Ministral/Magistral
Large 3 handler, but that template contains `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, which the v0.3 templates
do not have.  That difference is used as the primary distinguisher.

## Critical Files

| Path | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `common/chat.cpp` | Only file to change — add the new handler function and a new detection branch |
| `common/chat-peg-parser.h` | Reference only — `standard_json_tools()` is used in the new handler; **do not modify** |
| `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407.jinja` | Reference — confirms the `[INST]/[/INST]/[TOOL_CALLS]` token set |

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — Add the handler function

Insert the new static function **immediately before** the
`common_chat_try_specialized_template()` function (i.e. just before line 1634 in the
current file).  It must be placed after the last existing handler
(`common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3`, which ends around line 1517) and before the
`workaround::` namespace block is irrelevant — it must be before the dispatcher.

```cpp
// Handler for Mistral Instruct v0.3 format (e.g. Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407).
// Format:
//   - User turns:       [INST]{content}[/INST]
//   - System message:   prepended to first user turn by the Jinja template
//   - Assistant turns:  {content}</s>
//   - Tool calls:       [TOOL_CALLS][{"name":…,"arguments":{…},"id":"…"},…]</s>
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    const auto has_tools     = inputs.tools.is_array() && !inputs.tools.empty();
    const auto include_tools = has_tools && inputs.tool_choice != COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE;

    data.prompt           = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format           = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.preserved_tokens = { "[TOOL_CALLS]" };

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        if (include_tools) {
            // Tool-call section: [TOOL_CALLS][{"name":…,"arguments":{…},"id":"…"},…]
            // array_wrapped=true because the list is enclosed in [ ].
            // parameters_order matches the emission order in the Jinja template.
            auto tool_calls = p.trigger_rule(
                "tool-call",
                p.standard_json_tools(
                    "[TOOL_CALLS]", "",
                    inputs.tools, inputs.parallel_tool_calls,
                    inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_REQUIRED,
                    "name", "arguments",
                    /* array_wrapped   = */ true,
                    /* function_is_key = */ false,
                    /* call_id_key     = */ "id",
                    /* gen_call_id_key = */ "",
                    /* parameters_order = */ { "name", "arguments", "id" }
                )
            );
            return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) +
                   p.content(p.until("[TOOL_CALLS]")) +
                   tool_calls;
        }

        // Content-only response
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    if (include_tools) {
        data.grammar_lazy = inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_AUTO;
        data.grammar      = build_grammar([&](const common_grammar_builder & builder) {
            foreach_function(inputs.tools, [&](const json & tool) {
                const auto & function = tool.at("function");
                auto         schema   = function.at("parameters");
                builder.resolve_refs(schema);
            });
            parser.build_grammar(builder, data.grammar_lazy);
        });
        data.grammar_triggers = {
            { COMMON_GRAMMAR_TRIGGER_TYPE_WORD, "[TOOL_CALLS]" }
        };
    }

    return data;
}
```

### Step 2 — Register in the dispatch function

Inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`, add a new `if` block **after** the last
existing check (after the GigaChatV3 block, before `return std::nullopt`):

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 — [INST]/[/INST] user-turn format.
    // Distinguished from Ministral/Mistral Large 3 by the ABSENCE of [SYSTEM_PROMPT].
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v0.3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }

    return std::nullopt;
```

(Replace the existing bare `return std::nullopt;` — the new block is inserted just above
it, pushing `return std::nullopt;` to remain the final statement.)

## Key Design Decisions

- **Detection markers** — `[INST]` present + `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent.  The Ministral 3
  check (which requires `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`) runs first, so there is no risk of
  mis-routing Ministral templates here.
- **No reasoning support** — Mistral Instruct v0.3 is not a thinking model; the handler
  omits all `reasoning`/`thinking` infrastructure.
- **`standard_json_tools()` reuse** — This existing builder method handles the JSON-
  array tool-call layout (`array_wrapped=true`) and correctly tags `tool-open`,
  `tool-name`, `tool-args`, and `tool-id` nodes without bespoke parsing code.
- **Header unchanged** — The function is `static`, so no declaration is needed in
  `chat.h`.
- **No existing handler modified** — Only a new function is added and a new branch
  appended to the dispatcher.

## Verification

1. **Compile** — `cmake --build build -t llama-server` (or the project's usual build
   target). No new warnings should appear.

2. **Manual prompt check** — Run with the Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407 GGUF and pass
   `--verbose`.  The log should contain:
   ```
   Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v0.3
   ```

3. **Existing tests** — `./build/bin/test-chat-template` and
   `./build/bin/test-chat-auto-parser` must continue to pass unchanged.

4. **Tool-call round-trip** — Send a request with a tool definition using the Nemo
   model.  The server should return a `tool_calls` field in the assistant message with
   the correct `name`, `arguments`, and `id` values (9-char alphanumeric IDs as
   enforced by the Jinja template).

5. **System-message test** — Confirm that a `system` role message is rendered inside the
   first `[INST]…[/INST]` block (this is handled by the Jinja template itself; the
   handler calls `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl` with unmodified messages,
   which is correct).

